        <Parent_String>bagpipes [300042405], reedpipes with multiple pipes [300224176], reedpipes (confined aerophones) [300042558], reeds (aerophones) [300193013], aerophones [300041622], sound devices by acoustical characteristics [300041621], sound devices (equipment) [300387677], Sound Devices (hierarchy name) [300041619], Furnishings and Equipment (hierarchy name) [300264551], Objects Facet [300264092]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Bagpipes invented in the early 17th century, and frequently referred to as Italian musettes. The complex pipes were bellows-blown and had four separate chanters, two of which were partly keyed, and two that were completely keyed, enabling the user to produce four-part music.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000026541/Marcuse, Musical Instruments Dictionary (1975)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000006141/Bonanni, Antique Musical Instruments (1964)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>In de vroege 17de eeuw uitgevonden doedelzakken, vaak aangeduid als Italiaanse musettes. De complexe pijpen werden aangeblazen met een blaasbalg en hadden vier afzonderlijke schalmeien, waarvan twee gedeeltelijk met kleppen en twee volledig met kleppen, zodat de gebruiker vierstemmige muziek kon voortbrengen.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>十七世紀初發明的風笛，通常稱為義大利的彌賽特風笛。這種複雜的風笛為風箱式，並具有四支分開的指管，其中兩支部分具有按鍵、另兩支則完全為按鍵式，因此使用者可演奏出四聲部的音樂。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Sackpfeife, die im frühen 17. Jahrhundert erfunden wurde und oft als "Italienische Musette" bezeichnet wird. Die komplexe Pfeife war balggeblasen und hatte vier separate Melodiepfeifen, von denen zwei teilweise und zwei vollständig mit Klappen ausgestattet waren, sodass Vierstimmigkeit erzeugt werden konnte.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
